{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_cartier_ver01/data/sn94060041/00542866779/1930030101/0144.xml":{"full_text":"CAPE CHARLES\nMrs. John Goffigon, Sr. is quite\nill at her, home on Monroe Ave\nnue.\nMr. L. F. Schmidt left Wednesday\nto spend several days in Baltimore\non business.\nMr. F. Emmett Topping, of Rich\nmond, spent the week-end with Mrs.\nTopping here.\nMiss Fanny Thomas visited her\nsister, Miss Ruth Thomas in Nor\nfolk, for the week-end.\nMrs. C. H. Wagner has returned\nfrom a two'weeks\u2019 trip to Philadel\nphia and New York.\nMisses Grace Cowger, Beth Aga\nthoin and Mollie becates were in\nNew York for the week-end.\nMessrs. J. W. Wilson and E. T.\nMeelheirn have returned from a busi\nness trip to New York City.\nMisses Marie Taylor, Ruth Cox\nand Emily ^Milligan visited friends\nin Norfolk for the week-end.\nMiss Madeline Ross spent Satur\nday and Sunday with Mr. and Mrs.\nWharton P. Beahm in Richmond.\nMrs. J. E. Cushman, of New\nYork, is visiting her mother, Mrs.\nT. F. Mister, at her home near\nhere.\nMr. and Mrs. S. C. Chum visited\nMrs. Chum\u2019s parents, Mr. and Mrs.\nJ. F. East, at Onley, for the week\nend.\nMrs. W. B. Sweeney is spending\nsome time with Mrs. Ida Sweeney,\nwho is ill at her home in Williams\nburg.\nMr. and Mrs. C. A. Korn anil\nchildren, of Woodbury, N. J., were\nweek-end guests of Mr. and Mrs.\nM. S. Hall.\nMiss Beulah Windley, of Suffolk,\nis the guest of her aunt, Mrs. John\nF. Driscoll, ami Mr. Driscoll on Taze\nwell Avenue.\nMrs. W. S. Chandler is visiting\nher son, Shirley Chandler, who is\na student ait the University of Mary\nland, Baltimore.\nCadet H. H. Russell, Jr., of the\nVirginia Polytechnic Institute, spent\nthe week-end' with his parents, Mr.\n;ind Mrs. H. H. Russell.\nMiss Virginia Hughes, of the State\nTeachers\u2019 College, Fredericksburg,\nspent the week-end with her par\nents, Mr. and Mrs. -Vernon^ C. 7 Tay\nlor.\nCadet Aldon Brownley, of the Vir\nginia Polytechnic Institute, Blacks\nburg, spent the week-end with 'his\nparents, Captain and Mrs. J. F.\nBrownley.\nMiss Annie May Carty and Miss\nLouise Hancock, of Roanoke, were\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. N. F. Lam\nbertson on Tazewell Avenue for the\nweek-end.\nMr. Frank M. Fossett, of Balti\nmore, joined Mrs. Fossett, who has\nbeen visiting her parents, Mr. and\nMrs. G. E. Coulbourtr, on' Tazewell\nj Avenue, for the week-end.\nMr. and Mrs. B. \"Bi Stevenson and\nj children, Rosalynde and Garrick j\nj and Miss Aileen Melson motored to I\nPocomoke City, Md., where they vis-1\nj ited Mr. Stevenson's mother, Mrs.\nj C. E. Stevenson, for the week-end.\n1 Mrs. L. F. Schmidt and little non,\nLeo, Jr., left by automobile Monday\nto spend some time with relatives in J\nRichmond and Staunton. They were 1\naccompanied to Richmond by Miss\nJudith Eubank who is the guest of\n1 relatives at Millers Tavern, Va.\nMrs. Florence Thompson, Mrs. W.\nJ. Thompson and little Miss Dorothy\n1 Thompson have returned from Rich\nmond, where they attended the wed\nding of Air. Fred Thompson to Miss\n1 Issie Todd Gresham, which took place\nThursday, February 20th, at the\nhome of the bride\u2019s parents.\nI Mrs. E. L. Restein entertained at\nI tractively at three tables of bridge\nI Thursday afternoon at her home on\n1 Randolph Avenue. A very pretty\nprize was given for high score. The\nI home was prettily decorated with\nspring flowers. The guests included\nMrs. S. C. Churn, Mrs. H. C. Smith,\nMrs. E. P. Gladstone, Mrs. W. C.\nParsons, Miss Louise Gladstone, Mrs.\nW. F. Ayres, Mrs. Reginald Jones,\nMrs. S. K. Ames, Mrs. W. F. Wil\nkins, Mrs. J. V. Torbert, Mrs. John\nCaffe? and Mrs. J. W. Dillahunt.\nRefreshments were served.\nj 'Mrs. E. L. Restein was hostess\nMonday afternoon at her home on\nRandolph Avenue when she enter\nI tained at three tables of bridge in\nhonor of Miss Lelia Taylor whose\n1 engagement to Mr. Joseph Dunne, of\ni Richmond, was recently announced.\nMiss Taylor was given a lovely guest\nprize and Mrs. E. T. Stevens won top\nscore prize. Those present and play\ning in addition to the honor guest\nincluded Miss Virginia Wilson, Miss\nGeorgie Wilson, Miss Helen Grim\nmer, Mrs. C. P. King, Mrs. J. H.\nAnderson, of Pensacola, Fla., Mrs.\nC. L. Hallett, Mrs. Otto Lowe, Mrs.\nClarence Fitchett, Mrs, Elizabeth\nMoore Goffigon, Mrs. M. S. Hall and\nMrs. E. T. Stevens. Refreshments\nwere served at the conclusion of ihe\ngame.\n\nMrs. Elizabeth Moore Goffigon en\ntertained at an attractive handker\nchief shower at her home on the\nj Boulevard in compliment to Miss\nLelia Taylor, whose engagement to\n;Mr. Joseph Wilcox Dunne, of\u2019Rich\nmond, was announced recently, the\nwedding to take place in April.\nBridge was also played at three\ntables. The home was beautifully\ndecorated with various spring flow\ners carrying out a color scheme of\ngreen and yelldw in both the decora\ntions and refreshments. A unique\nfeature of the occasion was\u2019 a hand\nkerchief corsage which was pre\nsented to the bride elect and honor\nguest, in addition to a lovely guest\nprize. Mrs. E. L. Restein won prize\nfor high score. Those present and\nplaying in addition to the honor\nguest werfe Mids Helen\" Grimmer,\nMiss Virginia Wilson, Miss Georgie\nWilson, Miss Elizabeth Nottingham,\nMrs. E. T.; Stevehs, Mrs. Reginald\nJones, Mrs: Otto Lowe, Mrs. C. P.\nKing, Mrs. J. H. Anderson, of Pensa-'\ncola, Fla., Mrs. Curry Thomas and\nMrs. E. L. Restein.\nThe Northampton County Chapter\nDaughters' of the American Revolu\ntion entertained at the social hall\nof Centenary M.' E. Church, South,\nat their annual Washington\u2019s Birth\nday. celebration, Saturday evening.\nAn interesting /program was arrang\ned and the speakers .for the occa\nsion were the Very Rev. Dobson\nPeacock, D. D.,. Rector of Christ\nChurch, Norfolk, arul the Rev. Glen\nG. Vought, pastor of the Cape Char\nles Baptist Church. There were num\nbers by Mr. E.C. Grimmer, violinist,\naccompanied by Miss Helen Grimmer,\nand piano solos by Miss Miriam Kel\nlem. Mrs. J. S. MoMath sang \u201cThe\nStar Spangled Banner,\u201d and Mrs. H.\nC. Richardson a contralto solo. The\nRev. Henry W. Battle, D. D., of\nLower Northampton Baptist Church,\ndelivered the invocation and members\nof the local Boy Scout organization\ntook part in\\ the program, which\nwas in charge of Mrs. Ruth Willis.\nThe invitations included members of\nthe Sons of the Revolution, the local\nclergy, heads of the County High\nSchools, presidents of the patriotic\nand civic organizations and a num\nber of friends of the Chapter.\nPUN CrOTE AGUE\nMrs. J. E. LeGato spent Wednes\nday in Pocomoke.'\nMrs. M. F. Byrd hafe recently in\nstalled lights in her home.\nMrs. Reide Nicoils entertained at\ncards last Wednesday evening.\nDr. U. R. Drummond, of Eastville,\nwas a caller in town last Thursday.\nMrs. J. B. lingo Visited Miss An\nnie Porter in Belle Haven last Fri\nday.\nMrs. Chandler Taylor attended the\nhospital meeting >at Nassawadox\nlast Friday.\nMrs. Nina Reide spent Tuesday\nwith her mother, Mrs. E., S. Wise,\nof Craddockville.\nMrs. Floyd Nock, Jr. spent last\nMonday with her parents, Mr. and\nMrs. S. W. Ames. I\nRev. C. W., Hallman gave an ad\ndress at.. Broadwater Church last\n11 -a\nLLOYD BLAINE\ni DRUGS\n\nJewelry, Fancy Goods\nSilverware, Etc.\nPocomoke City, Maryland\nLamps of All\nStyles\nFloor, Bridge and Table\nModels of novel design. Both\nmetal and Polychrome Bases.\nAssortment of dainty shades,\nParchment, Georgette, etc., in\nTempting variety, all smartly\ntrimmed.\nVery unusual values at the\nnew prices.\nDo not delay making your\nselection.\n\nJ. T. Smullin Son\nFurniture, Floor Coverings\nPocomoke City\n_ __\nMaryland\nSunday afternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. Roland Wilkins had\nseveral guests from Jamesville for\nsupper last Sunday.\nMrs. Maggie Kilmon, of Onancock.i\nspent Tuesday in the home of Mr.j\nand Mrs. Frank Byrd. I\nMr. Stanley Guy, of Wilmington,\nspent the week-end with his parents,\nMr. and Mrs. Ben Guy.\nMr. George Mears, of the P. R.\nR. Co., Cape Charles, is at home\nsuffering with rheumatism.\nThe Young People\u2019s Missionary So\nciety was entertained by Miss Anna\nDrummond last Friday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Carroll Waterfield\nentertained a number of relatives\nlast Friday at a 4 o\u2019clock dinner.\nMiss Nannie Ames attended a\nbridge party last Tuesday at Acco\nmac given by Misses Sarah and Mir\niam Nock.\nMrs. Mary Walker, who has been\nwith Mrs. S. K. Martin at Harborton\nfor several weeks, is at home for an\nindefinite stay.\nMrs. Wessie Eason, after spend\ning the winter at Summit, N. J.,\narrived Monday for a visit to her\nsister, Mrs. (Jeorge Beach.\nMrs. L. D.' Mears, of Craddock\nville, was the supper guest of her\nson and daughter-in-law, Mr. and\nMrs. George Mears, last Sunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Fred Waterfield,\nMr. and Mrs. Edward Drummond and\nMiss Susie Drummond were guests\nlast Sunday of Mr. and Mrs. Calvin\nEvans, of Melfa.'\nMr. and-Mrs. Ellison Johnson, Mr.\nCharles Beach, Mrs. Albert Beach\nand son, George Thomas, of Con\ncord, Mrs. C. B. Davis, Miss Gladys\nDavis and Mrs. Clyde Hutchinson,\nof Craddockville, were guests last\nFriday afternoon of Mr. and. Mrs.\nJ. E. LeCato.\nEASTERN SHORE PUB\nLIC SERVICE COMPANY\nAt a regular meeting of the Board\nof Directors of the above named\nCompany held on January 21st, 1930,\nthe regular quarterly dividend of\n$1.50 per share oil the $6.00 Series\nCumulative Preferred Stock of the\nabove named Company anil the regu\nlar quarterly dividend of $1.6214 per\nshare on the $6.50 Series Cumulative\"\nPreferred Stock of. the said Company\nwere declared .and will be payable'oh\nSaturday, March-. 1st, 1930, to stock-\nholders on record of Saturday, Feb-\nruarv loth, 1930.\nFrank A. Mitchell, Treasurer.\nCooperation Means Progress--Progress Brings Success\nLooking Forward\nNo one can definitely forecast the outcome of\nthe 1930 white potato season.\nThere are so many \u201cifs\u201d to be considered, all of\nwhich enter into the making of potato prices: If\nsuch or such an acreage is planted; if our neghbors\nplant less; if competitive districts decrease or in\ncrease; if the weather is so and so or something\nelse; if the yield is light or heavy; if the season is\nnorrpal or abnormal; if there is an overlapping of\nthe early crop onto our crop, or an overlapping of\nour crop on the later crop; if the buying power of\nthe consumer is good or poor; if disease is prevalent;\nif the potatoes \u00abrry well all of these and more;\nIt seems as though the white potato business is\nlargely made up of \u201cifs\u201d and high cost of production.\nNothing else is certain. We all admit that the most\ndefinite thing at planting time is high cost of pro\nduction, but there are certain price indications al\nready before us that we should not choose to ignore.\nCertain advance trends even now serve to indicate\nthe price prospects of the coming season. Perhaps\nthe greatest of all is The Acreage That Is Planted,\nthen a second thing of the utmost importance is\nThe Purchasing Power of the Consumer the\nso-called business outlook. These are the big \"ifs\u201d\nthat we can estimate with some considerable degree\nof certainty at this time.\nLet us pause in our planting for a moment and\nconsider these two things.which practically make our\npotato prices.\n1. Prospective Planting: The indications are\nfor a larger acreage in the far South than in 1928,\nand practically the hame in the second early states,\nwhich includes all the potatoes marketed during our\nnormal season. The intention to increase plantings\napparently is picreasing every day, against all the\ndictates of sound business sense. For instance, The\nProduce News of February 22 carries this news item\nfrom Norfolk:\n\u201cVirginia Producers, Gambling\nOn Others* Dough, To\nPlant Big**\n\u201cThe heavy freezes of the last few days have\ncompletely ruined all growing\u2019 crops here for im\nmediate shipment, excepting kale and 90 per cent of\nthat is showing ofjf color and bud bum.\n\u201cThe farmers have lost heavily this Winter and\nFall on their crops, but they are real gamblers and\nare putting in a heavy crop of potatoes and other\nspring yields, as they believe that the place where\nyou lose money is the place to find it. Government\nexperts and other advisers are trying to get them to\ncut down the potato crop, but they are going to plant\nall the seed and guano they can get, for most of them\nare now gambling on someone else\u2019s money. They have\nlost their own already. Norfolk will grow 1,000,000\nbarrels of Spring tubers if they can get the seed\nand guano on credit.\u201d\nSuch items are disturbing when we consider the\nbusiness outlook and its effects on demand, especially\nas judged by present prices.\n2. The Prices Paid For Potatoes Today Indicate\nIn Advance A Big Trend Toward 1930 Price Levels:\nWe have found that seasons tend to run good or bad.\nSome years from the very beginning prices continue\nstrong due to a quick, large scale demand that offsets\nconsiderable fluctuations in supply. 1929 was such\na season. Even though the potato supply was not\nab normally low as many people seemed to believe, the\ndemand was very active due to consumer prosperity.\nThis year we already see a difference. At this time\nlast year Florida potatoes were close to the $12.00\nper barrel mark. Florida new potatoes are now\nselling (report received 2-25-30) in New York at\naround $6.50 per barrel, deducting 65c commission\nand $1.50 freight reduces this price $2.15, leaving\n$4.25 per barrel as the f. o. 1). price in Florida.\nDeducting assembling and grading costs the producer\ndoes not receive that amount. Old potatoes are $3.10\nper barrel f o. b. Presque Isle, and 100- pound bags,\nold stock, are selling for $2.50 on the New York\nmarket.\nThere is no particular reason from the supply\nstandpoint why Florida potatoes should sell cheaper\nthis year than last. True, the supply of new stock\nis somewhat greater but not great enough to have\nmuch effect on total supply of potatoes, and the old\nstock is less than last year\u2019s supply. The Actual\nCause of Low Prices At This Time Is Largely Due\nto the Poor Purchasing Power of the Consumer.\nCiovemmental facts show that this low purchasing\npower probaWy will continue into the latter half of\nthe 1930 season. If new potato prices are now $4.25\nb- flonda; old potatoes on a f. o. b. price of\n$3.10, \\yhat price does the Eastern Shore fanner\nexpect in June or July with a vastly increased\nsupply. It is certain that the increase in new pota\ntoes at that time will vastly offset the decrease in\nold stock at our shipping season.\nWe definitely find the two most vital \u201cifs\u201d the\ndefinite things which set the price of potatoes, already\navailable for the fanners\u2019 use, and that both are dead\nset against a high price this year; first, A Large\nAcreage in Prospect, and second, Low Purchasing\nPower of the Trade and Consumers, which lead us to\nemphasize the statement made by Director Jno. R.\nHutcheson in the last week\u2019s issues of the Eastern\nShore papers; namely, That the White Potato Farm\ner Will Determine the Price He Receives for His\nPotatoes. True, he will not determine it in the way\nthat we might wish. He is not able to grow a vast\nsupply and then arbitrarily set a profitable selling\npnce. No, he cannot fix the price that way; he\nfixes it by the size crop he grows. He fixes the\nprice when he determines the supply. We do not\nwant to be pessimistic or us<* scare heads, but frank\nly we are badly scared. It is our film belief that the\nprospective intended acreage will produce an ovei^\nsupply during our season, .which will fix the prices\nat very low levels.\nWe believe the farmer is planting heavily on\nmistaken assumptions. He believes there was a\nshortage of white potatoes last year. This is not\ntiU6. 360,000,000 bushels of potatoes is approxi*?\n\u2122ately the maximum crop that can be moved at\nprofitable prices even in good business years. The\nfinal figures of the white potato crop in 1929 were\n355,000,000 bushels. With old potatoes selling .at\n$3.10 at the present time, it certainly does not in\ndicate a shortage of potatoes. The second mistake,\nwhich is tending to increase acreage, is the farmer\u2019s\n\u202211 i the opportunity for selling\u2019 white potatoes\nWill be as good in 1930 as it was in 1929. This is\nnot true. The tremendous break in the stock market\ndestroyed the purchasing power of many people by\n(liiectly taking money from them. In the second\nplace, it slowed dowm industries and businesses, which\nlimits the earning power of a great many waged\nearners. In turn this directly will limit their pur\nchasing power even of such staples as white potatoes\n1,1,0 \"\u201c\"S'* a nnai inougnt. Each and\nevery farmer realizes the present futility of his own\nindividual efforts in controlling the national supply of\npotatoes and thereby determining prices, yet we all\nknow that the only sound method of farm relief is to\nproduce farm crops in normal amounts. All other\nmethods are doomed to failure; no large surplus of\nnon-pei ishables can be withheld from the market\nlong even if tiled the price level will fall. The\nAction of the Wheat Market and the Drop in\nCotton Prices Clearly Show That Any Effort to Con\ntrol Prices in Time of Oversupply by Purchase and\nStorage Only Excites the Farmers to Increase Pro\nduction Activity, thereby destroying the possibilities\nol success, immediately breaking the price on the\nmarkets, and losing the money that was invested in\nstorage purchases without any relief to the producer.\nIhe chance is even less in the case of perishables.\nThe problem is too big for the individual, and it is\ntoo big tor any one production district. It is a reg\nional and a national problem, and it can only be\nhandled successfully in a regional and national way.\nOn the other hand, that fact does not release the\nindividual or the local community from responsibility\nits success is entirely dependent upon the individ\nual farmers. It only emphasizes that the individual\ngrowers and the individual communities must be an\neffective part of a regional and national scheme to\nregulate production on a sound and profitable basis.\nAll of this indicates clearly to us that relief to the\npotato industry stabilization from year to year __\nmust come from within the industry\" itself; that it\nmust be a desire that has a widespread appeal and\nthe approval of every individual grower, manifested\nin a definite plan which he approves and practices It\nmust have the collective desire and will of the potato\ntanners put into practice. Every other plan is doom\ned to failure simply because the individual farmers\nwill not follow the program. Until all want it and\nail practice relief measures, relief will not come. It\nis a community effort. The means to carry out such\na plan are available without cost to the fanner Do\nwe want stabilization? If we want it bad enough\nwe can have it.\nEASTERN SHORE OF VIRGINIA PRODUCE EXCHANGE","height":"26676","width":"20036"}}
